# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In 1988, Chubu Electric Power Company sponsored a film about Beavers, called Beavers.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The beavers filmed for the production were hand-reared in a natural setting under the care of wildlife expert, William Carrick.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] Accustomed to the presence of humans, but untrained, the beavers went about their business while the camera crew watched.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The IMAX® camera began recording in February 1987 near Port Perry, Ontario in chilly waters under nearly 2 feet of ice.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] Mal Wolfe was behind the camera for the under-ice sequences.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The film is 34 minutes long and was produced by Stephen Low.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In 2008, Chubu Electric formed a joint venture with French utility company EDF to purchase coal.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In 2016, Chubu Electric acquired EDF Trading’s coal and freight business and passed it onto its subsidiary JERA.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] EDF Trading acquired a 33 per cent stake in JERA Trading as a part of the transaction while JERA took full control of the Amstuw BV, the operator of the Rietlanden coal terminal in the Netherlands and EDF Trading Australia.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In 2015, Chubu Electric and Tokyo Electric Power Company (TEPCO) created a 50:50 joint venture JERA to handle the upstream energy and Liquefied natural gas (LNG) fuel procurement for both companies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In March 2017, the two companies signed an agreement to integrate their fossil fuel power plants under the JERA joint venture.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The Fair Trade Commission (FTC) approved the integration plan in 13 October 2017.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In August 2013, Chubu announced it would acquire an 80% stake in the Tokyo-based electricity supplier, Diamond Corp, marking the firm's entry into a market usually associated with Tokyo Electric Power Company (TEPCO).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In November 2019, a consortium of Mitsubishi (80%) and Chubu Electric (20%) bought Dutch utility company Eneco for €4.1bn ($4.5bn).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In February 2024, Chubu Electric and Eneco signed an agreement to acquire 30 per cent of Ecowende, the developers of the Hollandse Kust West Offshore Wind Farm.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In April 2020, the logo mark was renewed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] On 18 September 2022, Chubu Electric Power announced that it was a part of an investor consortium led by Japan Industrial Partners seeking to buy Toshiba.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] Chubu Electric contributed ¥100 billion out of the ¥2 trillion (USD 15.2 billion) valuation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In May 2022, Chubu Electric bought some stake in Indian solar energy company OMC Power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] And in November 2024, Chubu Electric expanded its investment in OMC Power to boost energy transition in India.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In January 2026, the Nuclear Regulation Authority announced it had found that Chubu Electric had fabricated data about earthquake risks at Hamaoka Nuclear Power Plant, and suspended its safety evaluation for a potential plant restart.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The company has 197 separate generating units with a total capacity of 32,828 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The company has 183 separate hydro generating stations with a total capacity of 5,219 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] The company has 11 separate thermal power stations with a total capacity of 23,969 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] On 6 May 2011, Prime Minister Naoto Kan requested the Hamaoka Nuclear Power Plant be shut down as an earthquake of magnitude 8.0 or higher is estimated 87% likely to hit the area within the next 30 years.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] Kan wanted to avoid a possible repeat of the Fukushima I nuclear accidents.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] On 9 May 2011, Chubu Electric decided to comply with the government request.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In June, Chubu Electric received a ¥100 billion ($1.24 billion) loan from the Development Bank of Japan to finance natural gas purchases to make up the shortfall in power caused by the shutdown of Hamaoka.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In July 2011, a mayor in Shizuoka Prefecture and a group of residents filed a lawsuit seeking the permanent decommissioning of the reactors at the power plant .
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] 18–20 m breakwater walls were constructed around the nuclear power plant between 2011 and 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In January 2024, Chubu Electric president Kingo Hayashi told a news conference that the firm was keen on restarting the Unit No.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] 4 subject to the completion of environment and safety reviews by the Nuclear Regulation Authority (NRA).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In 2012, Chubu Electric proposed to build dry storage facilities to accommodate the spent fuel that has accumulated in the storage pools that were to be decommissioned.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] In August 2021, Chubu Electric reported that fire alarms had been triggered at the suspended Unit No.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/chubu-electric-power-company] There were no reported injuries or radiation leak and the company's statement reported that the local fire service confirmed that there was no fire.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The electric power industry in Japan covers the generation, transmission, distribution, and sale of electric energy in Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Japan consumed approximately 918 terawatt-hours (TWh) of electricity in 2014.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Before the 2011 Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, about a quarter of electricity in the country was generated by nuclear power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In the following years, most nuclear power plants have been on hold, being replaced mostly by coal and natural gas.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Solar power is a growing source of electricity, and Japan has the third largest solar installed capacity with about 50 GW as of 2017.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Japan's electricity production is characterized by a diverse energy mix, including nuclear, fossil fuels, renewable energy, and hydroelectric power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Japan has the second largest pumped-hydro storage installed capacity in the world after China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The electrical grid in Japan is isolated, with no international connections, and consists of four wide area synchronous grids.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Unusually, the Eastern and Western grids run at different frequencies (50 and 60 Hz respectively) and are connected by HVDC connections.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] This considerably limits the amount of electricity that can be transmitted between the north and south of the country.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] At the behest of the Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers, Nippon Hassōden became the Electric Power Development Co., Limited in the fifties; and almost all of the electricity sector that are not under the control by EPDC was privatized into nine government-granted monopolies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The Ryukyu Islands electricity provider was, during the USCAR era, publicly owned; it was privatized shortly after the islands' admission into Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In 2008, Japan consumed an average of 8507 kWh/person of electricity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] That was 115% of the EU15 average of 7409 kWh/person and 95% of the OECD average of 8991 kWh/person.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] calculates the share of renewable energies in gross electrical consumption.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Compared with other nations, electricity in Japan is relatively expensive.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Since the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, and the subsequent large scale shutdown on the nuclear power industry, Japan's ten regional electricity operators have been making very large financial losses, larger than US$15 billion in both 2012 and 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Since then steps have been made to liberalize the electricity supply market.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In April 2016 domestic and small business mains voltage customers became able to select from over 250 supplier companies competitively selling electricity, but many of them sell only locally, mainly in large cities.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Also wholesale electricity trading on the Japan Electric Power Exchange (JEPX), which previously traded only 1.5% of power generation, was encouraged.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] By June 2016 more than 1 million consumers had changed supplier.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] However total costs of liberalization to that point were around ¥80 billion, so it is unclear if consumers had benefited financially.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In 2020 transmission and distribution infrastructure access will be made more open, which will help competitive suppliers cut costs.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Electricity transmission in Japan is unusual because the country is divided for historical reasons into two regions each running at a different mains frequency.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Eastern Japan has 50 Hz networks while western Japan has 60 Hz networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Limitations of conversion capacity causes a bottleneck to transfer electricity and shift imbalances between the networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Eastern Japan (consisting of Hokkaido, Tohoku, Kanto, and eastern parts of Chubu) runs at 50 Hz; Western Japan (including most of Chubu, Kansai, Chugoku, Shikoku, and Kyushu) runs at 60 Hz.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] That originates from the first purchases of generators from AEG for Tokyo in 1895 and from General Electric for Osaka in 1896.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The frequency difference partitions Japan's national grid and so power can be moved only between the two parts of the grid using frequency converters, or HVDC transmission lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The boundary between the two regions has four back-to-back HVDC substations, which convert the frequency: Shin Shinano, Sakuma Dam, Minami-Fukumitsu, and the Higashi-Shimizu Frequency Converter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The total transmission capacity between the two grids is 1.2 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The limitations of these links have been a major problem in providing power to the areas of Japan affected by the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] During the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami, there were blackouts in some areas of the country because of the insufficient ability of the three HVDC converter stations to transfer energy between the two networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] A few projects are underway to increase the electricity transfer between the 50 Hz (eastern Japan) and 60 Hz networks (western Japan) which will improve power reliability in Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In April 2019, Hitachi ABB HVDC Technologies secured an HVDC order for the Higashi Shimizu project to increase the interconnection capacity between the 60 Hz area of Chubu Electric and the 50 Hz area of TEPCO from 1.2 GW to 3 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Chubu Electric will increase the interconnection capacity of the Higashi Shimizu Substation from 300 MW to 900 MW which should be operational by 2027.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] OCCTO (Organization for Cross-regional Coordination of Transmission Operators) supervises the power interchange among electric power companies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] According to the International Energy Agency, Japanese gross production of electricity was 1,041 TWh in 2009, making it the world's third largest producer of electricity with 5.2% of the world's electricity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] After Fukushima, Japan imported an additional 10 million short tons of coal and liquefied natural gas imports rose 24% between 2010 and 2012.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In 2012 Japan used most of its natural gas (64%) in the power sector.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Nuclear power was a national strategic priority in Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Following the 2011 Fukushima nuclear accidents, the national nuclear strategy is in doubt due to increasing public opposition to nuclear power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] An energy white paper, approved by the Japanese Cabinet in October 2011, reported that "public confidence in safety of nuclear power was greatly damaged" by the Fukushima disaster, and it calls for a reduction in the nation's reliance on nuclear power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Following the 2011 accident, many reactors were shut down for inspection and for upgrades to more stringent safety standards.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] By October 2011, only 11 nuclear power plants were operating in Japan, and all 50 nuclear reactors were offline by 15 September 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] That left Japan without nuclear energy for only the second time in almost 50 years.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Carbon dioxide emissions from the electricity industry rose in 2012, reaching levels 39% more than when the reactors were in operation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Sendai 1 reactor was restarted on 11 August 2015, the first reactor to meet new safety standards and be restarted after the shutdown.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] As of July 2018, there are nine reactors that have been restarted.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Hydroelectricity is Japan's main renewable energy source, with an installed capacity of about 27 GW, or 16% of the total generation capacity, of which about half is pumped-storage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] As of September 2011, Japan had 1,198 small hydropower plants with a total capacity of 3,225 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The smaller plants accounted for 6.6 percent of Japan's total hydropower capacity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The remaining capacity was filled by large and medium hydropower stations, typically sited at large dams.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] One result of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster could be renewed public support for the commercialization of renewable energy technologies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The Japanese government announced in May 2011 a goal of producing 20% of the nation's electricity from renewable sources, including solar, wind, and biomass, by the early 2020s.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In August 2011, the Japanese Government passed a bill to subsidize electricity from renewable energy sources.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] The legislation will become effective on 1 July 2012, and require utilities to buy electricity generated by renewable sources including solar power, wind power and geothermal energy at above-market rates.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In 2011 Japan planned to build as many as 80 floating wind turbines off Fukushima by 2020.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] In 2020, seven years after the world's first pilot floating wind turbine was installed off Fukushima in 2013, the Japanese government announced its withdrawal from the offshore wind farm.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] Japan relies mostly on pumped storage hydroelectricity to balance demand and supply.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/electricity-sector-in-japan] As of 2014, Japan has the largest pumped storage capacity in the world, with over 27 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan is a major consumer of energy, ranking fifth in the world by primary energy use.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Fossil fuels accounted for 67% of Japan's primary energy in 2023.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan imports most of its energy due to scarce domestic resources.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2022, the country imports 97% of its oil and is the largest liquefied natural gas (LNG) importer globally.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan is increasing its reliance on renewable energy to replace imported fossil fuels, and in 2019 renewable energy accounted for 7.8% of primary energy supply.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has committed to reaching net zero emissions by 2050, setting a target to reduce GHG emissions by 60% from year 2013 levels by 2035 and by 73% by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In addition, the 7th Strategic energy Plan has also set the renewable share goal to be 40-50% by the year 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2024, the share of renewable energy in total electricity generation reached 26.7%, an increase from 25.7% in 2023.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan initiated its first commercial nuclear power reactor in 1966, establishing nuclear energy as a strategic national priority from 1973 onwards.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Following the Fukushima nuclear accident in 2011, this strategy underwent re-evaluation and new plans were introduced to proactively utilize nuclear power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Prior to the accident, nuclear reactors contributed about 30% of Japan's electricity, with the country now aiming for nuclear energy to account for at least 20% of its electricity production by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Fukushima accident also led to a 16% reduction in total primary energy supply (TPES) from 2010 to 2019.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, because of current needs of Digital Transformation (DX) and Green Transformation (GX) from the massive need of electricity from AI, data centers, and semiconductor manufacturing, the demand for electricity is expected to increase.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Moreover, the government has also made a goal to raise Japan's energy self-sufficiency rate to about 30 to 40% by Fiscal year 2040.Therefore, it is more likely that the usage of nuclear power will increase.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In the post-war period, Japan's energy policy underwent significant transformation as it grappled with limited domestic energy resources.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Initially, Japan relied heavily on coal, which accounted for over 80% of its energy needs in the 1950s, fueling its rapid industrialization and supporting its economic recovery.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Coal was integral to powering factories, railways, and other critical infrastructure.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, by the late 1950s and early 1960s, Japan shifted towards oil due to its cost-effectiveness, higher energy density, and the challenges posed by domestic coal supply disruptions.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By the 1970s, oil dominated Japan's energy mix, accounting for over 70% of its energy requirements, driven by rapid urbanization and the expansion of the transportation and manufacturing sectors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The 1973 oil crisis marked a turning point, exposing Japan's vulnerability to external supply shocks and triggering efforts to diversify its energy sources.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This period saw the emergence of liquefied natural gas (LNG) as a viable alternative, valued for its lower environmental impact, flexibility, and increasing global availability.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan signed its first LNG import agreement in 1967, and by the 1990s, partnerships with countries in the Middle East, particularly Qatar, solidified LNG as a cornerstone of its energy policy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] These energy shifts—from coal to oil to LNG—reflect Japan's strategic adaptation to global energy dynamics, ensuring a stable supply while fostering deeper economic and political ties with resource-rich regions like the Gulf.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's rapid industrial growth since the end of World War II doubled the nation's energy consumption every five years into the 1990s.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] During the 1960–72 period of accelerated growth, energy consumption grew much faster than GNP, doubling Japan's consumption of world energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By 1976, with only 3% of the world's population, Japan was consuming 6% of global energy supplies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Compared with other nations, electricity in Japan is relatively expensive, and, since the loss of nuclear power after the earthquake and tsunami disaster at Fukushima, the cost of electricity has risen significantly.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] After the 2011 Fukushima nuclear accident the government made major revisions, which were first outlined in the 2014 Strategic Energy Plan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] These revisions focused on restructuring the FIT (feed-in tariff) system, prioritizing disseminating renewable resources over fossil fuels, and using Fukushima as a hub for non-fossil fuel energy industries.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The COVID-19 pandemic had a significant impact on energy consumption.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Although 2020-2021 energy emissions were stable, consumption rebounded in 2022.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 1950, coal supplied half of Japan's energy needs, hydroelectricity one-third, and oil the rest.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By 2001, the contribution of oil had increased to 50.2% of the total, with rises also in the use of nuclear power and natural gas.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan now depends heavily on imported fossil fuels to meet its energy demand.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2024, electricity generated from fossil fuels fell to 65.1% lower compared to 66.6% the previous year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Yet, both natural gas and coal remained largely unchanged: LNG at 29.1% and coal at 28.2%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In the wake of the two oil crises of the 1970s (1973 and 1979), Japan made efforts to diversify energy resources in order to increase energy security.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's domestic oil consumption dropped slightly, from around 5.1 million barrels (810,000 m3) of oil per day in the late 1980s to 4.9 million barrels (780,000 m3) per day in 1990.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] While the country's use of oil declined, its use of nuclear power and natural gas rose substantially.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Several Japanese industries, for example electric power companies and steelmakers, switched from petroleum to coal, most of which is imported.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's proved oil reserves total an estimated 44 million barrels.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The state stockpile equals about 92 days of consumption and the privately held stockpiles equal another 77 days of consumption for a total of 169 days or 579 million barrels (92,100,000 m3).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Japanese SPR is run by the Japan Oil, Gas and Metals National Corporation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan was the fifth-largest oil consumer and fourth-largest crude oil importer in the world in 2019.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Oil demand has been waning in Japan, especially leading up to and since the Tohoku earthquake in 2011.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] While oil consumption was over 5 million barrels per day (bpd) for decades, this had declined to 3.22 million bpd by 2017.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2016, India, Saudi Arabia and Texas have overtaken Japan in oil consumption.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] A further decline to 3.03 mln bpd or just under 176 million kiloliters (preliminary) was posted in 2018.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Crude consumption further declined during first half of 2020 to 303/141 = 2.15 million bpd, but that figure probably doesn't include refined products that are directly increasingly imported rather than converted.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, Japan's crude oil imports rose to 2.5 million barrels per day (b/d), an increase from 2.3 million b/d in 2021, despite a decade-long trend of declining imports, which are now almost 0.9 million b/d less than the 2013 levels.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Middle East remained the predominant source, accounting for 93% of imports.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Concurrently, Japan's crude oil acquisitions from Russia declined to 1% of the total, a decrease from 4% in the preceding year, in the aftermath of Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan ranked as the world's largest importer of liquefied natural gas (LNG).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Because domestic natural gas production is minimal, rising demand is met by greater imports.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's main LNG suppliers in 2016 were Australia (27%), Malaysia (18%), Qatar (15%), Russia (9%), and Indonesia (8%).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2017, Japan consumed 4.7 quadrillion Btu (1377 TWh) of imported methane.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The new Japanese LNG strategy published in May 2016 envisages the creation of a liquid market and an international LNG hub in Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This promises to radically change the traditional JCC (crude oil) based pricing system in Japan, but also potentially in the Pacific Basin as a whole.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] But the path to hub creation and hub pricing in the early 2020s envisaged by the Strategy will not be straightforward.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, Japan's LNG imports decreased to 3.3 Tcf from 3.6 Tcf in 2021, yet it remained the world's leading LNG importer, surpassing China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Australia's contribution to Japan's imports increased from 36% to 42%, affirming its status as Japan's primary LNG supplier.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Conversely, Qatar's share fell from 13% to 4%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Despite Japan's commitment to reducing energy dependence on Russia, in line with the G7's price cap on Russian crude oil, its LNG imports from Russia remained steady, supported by an exemption for the Sakhalin-2 project.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has set a policy goal to reduce the share of LNG in its power generation from 34% in 2022 to 20% by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As the largest single source of power in 2022, accounting for 34%, LNG consumption has seen a decline since 2019, influenced by the reactivation of nuclear plants, slow economic growth, high international LNG prices, and enhanced energy efficiency.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan holds the largest LNG storage capacity in the world, estimated at 425.1 billion cubic feet, which plays a critical role in managing seasonal demand fluctuations and potential supply disruptions.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Furthermore, from 2009 to 2023, the levels of LNG inventory in Japan varied between 32% and 66% of its storage capacity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's engagement with Middle Eastern nations, particularly Qatar, has played a crucial role in shaping its liquefied natural gas (LNG) imports and energy security.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Following the adoption of LNG in the 1960s, Japan's shift towards cleaner and cost-effective energy sources has led to long-term partnerships with Gulf states.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Qatar, home to the world's largest non-associated gas field, became a dominant LNG supplier to Japan in 1997, with agreements prioritizing reliability, cost optimization, and integrated supply systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] These ties have not only contributed to Japan's energy stability but also strengthened bilateral trade and technological cooperation, reflecting a broader interdependence between Japan and the Gulf region.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Under the 7th Strategic Energy Plan, Japan has raised its self-development target ratio for oil and natural gas to over 50% by 2030 and 60% by 2040, increasing equity participation in overseas projects.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] While Japan will continue to rely on LNG, they are also working to decarbonize the LNG value chain and reduce emissions.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2019, a third of the electricity in Japan was generated from coal and is the third-largest importer of coal behind China and India in 2019.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Government targets aimed to reduce that proportion to a quarter through closure of older, less efficient coal power plants.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2017, Japan consumed 4.738 quadrillion Btu (1,388 TWh) of imported coal.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In July 2020, the minister of Industry, Hiroshi Kajiyama, announced that around 100 coal plants would be shut down by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2023 Japan said it would not start building any more new unabated (without carbon capture and storage) coal plants.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan plans to phase out unabated coal by 2035.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, Japan's coal imports remained at 202 million short tons.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Russian imports significantly decreased from 22 million to 13 million short tons, offset by increases from Indonesia, Canada, and Australia.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Bituminous coal made up 89% of steam coal imports, slightly down from the previous year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The main sources—Australia, Indonesia, Russia, and the United States—contributed 94% of the total, a 3% decrease from 2021.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The contribution of coal-fired power generation decreased from 30.2% in 2016 to 26.5% in 2021, but then saw an increase to 27.8% in 2022.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has set a policy goal to reduce the share of coal in electricity generation from 31% in 2022 to 19% by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As part of this initiative, there are plans to close or suspend about 90% of inefficient coal-fired power plants, which amounts to approximately 100 facilities, thereby reducing Japan's total installed coal capacity by about 40%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Additionally, to further mitigate environmental impact, new coal-fired power plants are required to incorporate emission reduction measures, such as blending coal with 20% ammonia or 25% wood pellets to significantly lower carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Following Eisenhower's Atoms for Peace speech, the United States helped Japan develop their nuclear power program.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] When Japan decided to embark on the nuclear power field, it imported technology from the United States and obtained uranium from Canada, France, South Africa, and Australia.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The first nuclear reactor was commissioned in 1966, from then to 2010, 54 more nuclear reactors had opened, with total generation capacity of 48,847 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The ratio of nuclear power generation to total electricity production increased from 2% in 1973 to around 30% in March 2011.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] During the 1980s, Japan's nuclear power program was strongly opposed by environmental groups, particularly after the Three Mile Island accident in the United States.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In the 2000s, Japan had a few of the modern Advanced Boiling Water Reactor, including some of the first new advanced Generation III reactors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] At Rokkasho, Aomori a facility was built to enrich nuclear fuel, deal with nuclear waste, and recycle spent nuclear fuel.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami damaged some nuclear reactors, and was the immediate cause of the Fukushima nuclear accident.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This caused much uncertainty and fear about the release of radioactive material, as well as highlighting the ongoing concerns over seismic design standards (see Nuclear power in Japan §Seismicity).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] On 5 May 2012, Japan shut down the last nuclear reactor, the first time there has been no nuclear power production since 1970.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] On 16 June, Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda ordered the restart of Ōi nuclear plant's reactors number 3 and 4, saying that people's livelihood needs to be protected. Ōi nuclear plant's reactor No.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, in September 2013 the plant was shut down again in order to have extensive safety inspections performed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By late 2015, both of the Sendai Nuclear Power Plant's reactors had reopened and restarted producing nuclear energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Other nuclear plants, such as the Takahama Nuclear Power Plant, have received permission to reopen, and other nuclear reactors are beginning the process of restarting.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In a draft of Japan's seventh long-term energy plan (December 2024), the Japanese government expresses the aim that nuclear power should account for 20% of Japan's energy supply by 2040, rising from 8.5% in 2023.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This goal was raised to increase Japan's energy self-sufficiency rate to approximately 30 to 40% by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's 7th Strategic Energy Plan further emphasizes the proactive use of nuclear power, driven by the growing energy demand for more energy with Digital Transformation (DX) and Green Transformation (GX).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has restructured the usage of nuclear power in several ways.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] One is to rebuild a new advanced reactor that incorporates enhanced safety mechanisms and will only be approved with the consent of local communities.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In addition, under the GX Decarbonization Power Source Act, a new system is proposed that excludes periods of shutdown from the 60-year maximum operating limit.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Moreover, Japan will continue to promote its nuclear fuel recycling system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The plan is to reprocess used nuclear fuel to extract plutonium, which can then be reused as MOX fuel in nuclear reactors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan aims to have at least 12 reactors using MOX fuel by FY2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The government is currently working towards the completion of the Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant and MOX Fuel Fabrication Plant.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As a result, compared to the 7.7% share of nuclear generation in 2023, it has risen to 8.2% in 2024.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The policy to increase the share of nuclear energy, which dates from 2015, reversed a decision by the previous Democratic Party.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Fourth Strategic Energy Plan set the renewable share goal to be 40 to 50% by fiscal year 2040.In the next 15 years, Japan intends on investing $700 billion into renewable energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] One initiative the Japanese government has implemented in order to boost the amount of renewable energy produced and purchased in Japan is the feed-in tariff scheme.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan had transitioned from the previous Renewable Portfolio Standards (RPS) to shifting investment to a Feed-in-Tariff (FIT) in July 2012.The scheme encourages companies to invest in renewable energy by providing set prices for various types of renewable energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The initiatives appear to be working, as renewable energy generation capacity now stands at 26.2 GW, compared to 20.9 GW in 2012.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] On 3 July 2018, Japan's government pledged to increase renewable energy sources, including wind and solar, from 15% to 22–24% by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Nuclear power will provide 20% of the country's energy needs as an emissions-free energy source.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This will help Japan meet climate change commitments.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In October 2021 Japan's cabinet approved a new target of 36–38% of renewable share in power generation by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The nuclear target of 20–22% remained unchanged.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, renewables are estimated to make up 22.7% of Japan's overall electricity generation, including consumption at the site of generation, which is a slight rise from 22.4% in the previous year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2024, the share of renewable energy in total electricity generation reached 26.7%, an increased from 25.7% in 2023.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The country's main renewable energy source is hydroelectricity, with an installed capacity of about 27 GW and a production of 69.2 TWh of electricity in 2009.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] There are still 14,440 MW of potential small and medium-scale hydropower that can be implemented in Japan, according to the Ministry of the Environment.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In recent years, Japan has focused particularly on mini and micro hydropower facilities, especially in mountainous regions that have less environmental impact.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan was the world's second largest producer of solar power in the early 2000s, although solar was a very minor contribution to the total at that time.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The country was overtaken by Germany in 2005, a year in which Japan had 38% of the world supply compared to Germany's 39%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Since then, Japan had been slow to increase solar capacity compared to other countries until 2012.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] On 1 July 2012, after the nuclear disaster at Fukushima, new tariffs for renewable energy were introduced by the Japanese government.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The tariffs, set at ¥42 per kWh over the next 20 years to solar power producers, were among the highest in the world.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] With the incentives in place, Japan added 1,718 MW of solar power in 2012.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By the end of the year, Japan's total solar capacity was 7.4 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has seen sustained growth of solar PV capacity after 2012, reaching a cumulative installed capacity of 34 GW by the end of 2015, generating 3.5% of the national electricity consumption in that year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, electricity produced by solar photovoltaic (PV) systems amounted to 9.9% of the total annual electricity output, reflecting a growth of 0.6 percentage points from 9.3% in 2021.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2024, the usage of solar power has reached 11.4%, slowly approaching the 15% target goal for 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In Japan's electricity sector, wind power generates a small proportion of the country's electricity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] It has been estimated that Japan has the potential for 144 gigawatts (GW) for onshore wind and 608 GW of offshore wind capacity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2023, the country had a total installed capacity of 5.2 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2018, government targets for wind power deployment were relatively low when compared to other countries, at 1.7% of electricity production by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In December 2020, the Japanese government announced plans to install up to 45 GW of offshore wind power by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, wind power contributed to 0.85% of electricity production, experiencing a slight decrease from 0.88% in the previous year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has favorable sites for geothermal power because of its proximity to the Izu–Bonin–Mariana Arc.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2007, Japan had 535.2 MW of installed electric generating capacity, about 5% of the world total.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Geothermal power plays a minor role in the energy sector in the country: in 2013 it supplied 2596 GWh of electricity, representing about 0.25% of the country's total electricity supply.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Development of new geothermal power stations has slowed since the mid-1990s.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Many potential sites are situated in government-protected areas and popular tourist destinations, including traditional hot springs or onsen.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Hot springs are a notable aspect of Japan's onsen culture and are often considered in discussions about energy policy and geothermal development due to their cultural and economic roles.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Local communities in these areas, which frequently depend on tourism revenue from onsen, have expressed reservations about the potential impact of geothermal projects on the landscape and the tourism industry.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Sumikawa Geothermal Power Station, located within Towada-Hachimantai National Park, is one of Japan's eighteen geothermal power sites and one of seven in the northern Honshu region (Tohoku).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Operating since 1995, the Sumikawa Geothermal Power Station generates 50,000 kW of electrical energy and hot water, supporting the city of Kazuno and surrounding areas, home to approximately 32,000 residents.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Geothermal energy has been increasing in recent years due to the Japanese energy crisis following the Fukushima disaster and the subsequent closure of most of the country's nuclear power stations.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Businesses and the government are currently considering over 60 possible sites for new geothermal power development.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Estimated total capacity potential of geothermal power at 23 GW, the third largest amount in the world after the United States and Indonesia.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan ranks third in the world in terms of geothermal potential, with more than 100 volcanoes contributing to its energy prospects.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Out of the 100 volcanoes with geothermal energy potential, most of Japan's 20 major geothermal power plants are in the Tohoku and Kyushu regions, which are home to some of the country's most abundant hot springs.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Geothermal energy development in Japan faces significant challenges in balancing energy development with the preservation of the traditional hot spring (onsen) culture.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] While having the world's third-largest geothermal energy potential, many residents are concerned that hot springs may become scarce.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] These concerns are particularly common in tourist areas such as Beppu, where hot springs play an essential role in both local culture and the economy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In addition, about 80% of Japan's geothermal resources are located within national parks or places with similar protection, where strict environmental regulations, such as those under the Natural Parks Act and Hot Springs Act, complicate permissions related to hot springs.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The 2025 draft of the 7th Strategic Energy Plan introduced the Geothermal Frontier Project and the Accelerated Geothermal Development Package.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] These initiatives aim to expand scientific knowledge of geothermal resources while ensuring that local hot spring businesses are respected and supported through community consent.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of September 2011, Japan had 190 generators attached to municipal waste units and 70 independent plants using biomass fuel to produce energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In addition, 14 other generators were used to burn both coal and biomass fuel.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2008, Japan produced 322 million tons of biomass fuel and converted 76% of it into energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2022, the proportion of electricity generated from biomass power rose to 4.6%, an increase from 4.1% in the preceding year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2012, the government announced plans to build experimental tidal power and wave power plants in coastal areas.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Construction on the projects, the locations for which have not been determined, would begin in 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] There is a potential for generating tidal power in the Seto Inland Sea, which contributes to Japan's 2050 carbon neutrality goal.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Using high-resolution ocean modeling, researchers have identified several locations suitable for tidal energy development, such as the Naruto Strait, the Akashi Strait, the Kurushima Strait, and the Obatake Strait.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The study concluded that installing tidal turbines at the Obatake Strait in Yamaguchi Prefecture could supply electricity to approximately 100,000 households.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Moreover, implementing the Obatake Stait project would help reduce carbon emissions by about 198,000 tons of CO2 per year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's energy sector has experienced a significant expansion of renewable energy capacity, growing by over 30% in the past five years, fueling demand for battery energy storage systems (BESS).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Over half of the 2.4 gigawatts of capacity awarded in recent long-term low-carbon power auctions went to foreign companies or consortia, with major projects including over 1.37 GW of new BESS capacity and more than 6.7 GWh of energy capacity approved for 2024.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan's Long Term Decarbonization Power Source Auction incentivizes BESS development by guaranteeing fixed cost recovery for 20 years.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, limited price volatility and a price floor in the Japanese power market may constrain returns for BESS operators, highlighting the need for further reforms.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2014, Japan ranked fifth in the world by electricity production, after the United States, China, Russia, and India with 934 TWh produced during that year.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] It is estimated that Japan's net electricity generation was at about 950 terawatthours (TWh) in 2019 and has declined overall by about 11% since 2010.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 2019, Japan's net electricity generation decreased nearly 4% from the 2018 level as a result of warm winter weather and lower industrial output.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In terms of per capita electricity consumption, the average person in Japan consumed 8,459 kWh in 2004 compared to 14,240 kWh for the average American.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In that respect it ranked 18th among the countries of the world.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Its per capita electricity consumption increased by 21.8% between 1990 and 2004.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan had 282 GW of total installed electricity generating capacity in 2010, the third largest in the world behind the United States and China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, after the damage by the 2011 earthquake, capacity is estimated to be around 243 GW in mid-2011.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] It was one of the world's largest users of solar energy, in fourth place behind Germany, Italy, and China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] With 53 active nuclear power generating reactor units in 2009, that year Japan ranked third in the world in that respect, after the United States (104 reactors) and France (59).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Almost one quarter (24.93%) of its electricity production was from nuclear plants, compared to 76.18% for France and 19.66% for the United States.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, after the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami and the subsequent Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, all plants eventually shut down in May 2012 and Ōi Nuclear Power Plant was restarted and operational between June 2012 and September 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] On 11 August 2015 and 1 November 2015, the two nuclear reactors of Sendai Nuclear Power Plant were restarted respectively.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Since the generation disruption caused by the Fukushima disaster, rapid steps have been made to liberalize the electricity market.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] One way this was done in Japan is through the feed-in-tariff scheme.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This was announced in 2012 as a direct consequence of the Fukushima disaster.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The feed-in-tariff scheme encourages utility operators and companies to purchase and invest in renewable energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry set prices for various renewable energy sources to encourage the production and consumption of renewable energy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In April 2016 domestic and small business customers became able to select from over 250 supplier companies competitively selling electricity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Also wholesale electricity trading on the Japan Electric Power Exchange has been encouraged.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan produced 1004.8 TWh of electricity in 2021, close to 4% of the electricity generated in the world and 8% of that in Asia-Pacific (3rd largest behind China and India).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan consumed 17.03 EJ, 3% of the world's consumption and 7% of Asia-Pacific's consumption (3rd largest behind China and India).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Nuclear energy's contribution to electricity generation has fluctuated, dropping to zero in 2014, then climbing to 6.5% by 2019.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] It fell to 4.3% in 2020, slightly rose to 5.9% in 2021, and then decreased once more to 4.8% in 2022.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] As of 2024, renewable energy accounted for 26.7% of Japan's total electricity generation, up from previous year of 25.7%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Specifically, solar contributed 11.4%, hydropower 7.9%, biomass 5.9%, and wind 1.13%.The government plans to use public bidding under Japan's Offshore Renewable Energy Act to develop 10 GW of offshore renewable energy projects by 2030 and 30-45 GW by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Furthermore, Japan aims to steadily reduce the cost of renewable electricity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Specifically, they are aiming to drop the amount to 20 yen/ kWh by 2025, 14 yen/kWh by 2030, and 10-14 yen/kWh by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The government also plans to increase domestic manufacturing of renewable energy equipment by 2030.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Cooperation between the government and private companies is considered essential to enable mass production and global competitiveness.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Ultimately, the government hopes to achieve 20 GW of installed renewable electricity capacity by 2040.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Because Japan is shifting more towards renewable energy, the demand for grid-scale battery storage is growing.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Maintaining a balance between supply and demand is being prioritized.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By March 2025, applications to connect large batteries to the grid had reached about 113 GW, demonstrating strong market interest.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] However, only 12 GW have been approved due to transmission limits and grid congestion.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This is because Japan's electric system currently has more residential batteries than large utility systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In order for Japan to integrate large-scale storage, uprgrading the grid and expanding utility-scale storage is necessary to improve overall system flexibility.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Unlike most other industrial countries, Japan doesn't have a single national grid but instead has separate eastern and western grids.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The standard voltage at power outlets is 100 V, but the grids operate at different frequencies: 50 Hz in Eastern Japan and 60 Hz in Western Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The grids are connected together by three frequency converter stations (Higashi-Shimizu, Shin Shinano and Sakuma), but these can only handle 1 GW in total.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] A converter station also exists at Minami-Fukumitsu.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami resulted in 11 reactors being taken offline with a loss of 9.7GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The three converter stations did not have the capacity to transfer enough power from Japan's western power grid to significantly help the eastern grid.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The two grids were originally developed by separate companies.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Tokyo Electric Light Co was established in 1883, which also established electric power in Japan.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In 1895, demand had grown enough that TELCO bought generation equipment from AEG of Germany.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] The same happened in the western parts of Japan with General Electric being the supplier to Osaka Electric Lamp.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] GE's equipment used the US standard of 60 Hz, while AEG's equipment used the European standard of 50 Hz.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] In March 2016, METI set a target of 40,000 hydrogen fuel-cell vehicles on Japan's roads by 2020 and 160 fueling stations.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Japan has a goal of net zero greenhouse gas emissions by 2050.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Achieving this target will require changes in daily life to focus on lowering energy demand.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This starts with saving electricity in buildings and factories.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Moreover, Japan needs to invest in low-carbon technologies such as nuclear power and carbon capture.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Geopolitical tensions, such as the Russian invasion of Ukraine, have strengthened Japan's resource diplomacy.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] This includes financial support from Japan Oil, Gas and Metals National Corporation (JOGMEC) and developing systems to secure emergency gas supplies with the help of the International Energy Agency (IEA).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] Moreover, in recent years, Japan has focused on Green Economic Diplomacy, where it provides advanced green technology to emerging countries in exchange for stronger partnerships, particularly in LNG and oil imports.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/energy-in-japan] By doing so, Japan aims to stabilize its energy system despite its scarce domestic energy resources.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter] The Higashi-Shimizu Frequency Converter Station is operated by Chubu Electric Power Co. and is located at 677-3 Tanakake, Hirose-aza, Shimizu-ku, Shizuoka.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter] It is fed via a 275 kV power line and a 154 kV power line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter] Its inverters operate at 125 kVDC and have a maximum transmission rate of 300 MW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter] Japan's other converter stations are at Shin-Shinano in Nagano Prefecture, Sakuma Dam in Shizuoka Prefecture, and Minami-Fukumitsu in Toyama Prefecture.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A **high-voltage direct current** (**HVDC**) system uses direct current (DC) and high voltages (currently between 100 kV and 800 kV) for electric power transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] It contrasts with the more common alternating current (AC) transmission systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC lines are commonly used for long-distance power transmission, since they require fewer conductors and incur less power loss than equivalent AC lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC also allows power transmission between AC transmission systems that are not synchronized.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since the power flow through an HVDC link can be controlled independently of the phase angle between source and load, it can stabilize a network against disturbances due to rapid changes in power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC also allows the transfer of power between grid systems running at different frequencies, such as 50 and 60 Hz.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This improves the stability and economy of each grid, by allowing the exchange of power between previously incompatible networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The modern form of HVDC transmission uses technology developed extensively in the 1930s in Sweden (ASEA) and in Germany.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Early commercial installations included one in the Soviet Union in 1951 between Moscow and Kashira, and a 100 kV, 20 MW system between Gotland and mainland Sweden in 1954.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The longest HVDC link in the world is the Zhundong–South Anhui link in China, a ±1,100 kV, ultra HVDC line with a length of more than 3,000 km (1,900 mi).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] High voltage is used for electric power transmission to reduce the energy lost in the resistance of the wires.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since the energy lost as heat in the wires is directly proportional to the square of the current ${\textstyle ({\text{energy lost as heat}}={\text{current}}^{2}\cdot {\text{resistance}}\cdot {\text{time}}),}$ using half the current at double the voltage reduces the line losses by a factor of 4.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] While energy lost in transmission can also be reduced by decreasing the resistance by increasing the conductor size, larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] High voltage cannot readily be used for lighting or motors, so transmission-level voltages must be reduced for end-use equipment.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Transformers are used to change the voltage levels in alternating current (AC) transmission circuits, but cannot pass DC current.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Transformers make AC voltage changes practical, and AC generators are more efficient than those using DC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] These advantages led to early low-voltage DC transmission systems being supplanted by AC systems around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The first long-distance transmission of electric power was demonstrated using direct current in 1882 in the 57 km Miesbach-Munich Power Transmission, but only 1.5 kW was transmitted.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An early method of HVDC transmission was developed by the Swiss engineer René Thury and his method, the Thury system, was put into practice by 1889 in Italy by the Acquedotto De Ferrari-Galliera company.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This system used series-connected motor-generator sets to increase the voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Each set was insulated from electrical ground and driven by insulated shafts from a prime mover.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The transmission line was operated in a constant-current mode, with up to 5,000 volts across each machine, some machines having double commutators to reduce the voltage on each commutator.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This system transmitted 630 kW at 14 kV DC over a distance of 120 kilometres (75 mi).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The Moutiers–Lyon system transmitted 8,600 kW of hydroelectric power a distance of 200 kilometres (120 mi), including 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) of underground cable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This system used eight series-connected generators with dual commutators for a total voltage of 150 kV between the positive and negative poles, and operated from c.1906 until 1936.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Fifteen Thury systems were in operation by 1913.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Other Thury systems operating at up to 100 kV DC worked into the 1930s, but the rotating machinery required high maintenance and had high energy loss.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Various other electromechanical devices were tested during the first half of the 20th century with little commercial success.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] One technique attempted for conversion of direct current from a high transmission voltage to lower utilization voltage was to charge series-connected batteries, then reconnect the batteries in parallel to serve distribution loads.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] First proposed in 1914, the grid controlled mercury-arc valve became available during the period 1920 to 1940 for the rectifier and inverter functions associated with DC transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Starting in 1932, General Electric tested mercury-vapor valves and a 12 kV DC transmission line, which also served to convert 40 Hz generation to serve 60 Hz loads, at Mechanicville, New York.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In 1941, a 60 MW, ±200 kV, 115 km (71 mi) buried cable link, known as the Elbe-Project, was designed for the city of Berlin using mercury arc valves but, owing to the collapse of the German government in 1945, the project was never completed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The nominal justification for the project was that, during wartime, a buried cable would be less conspicuous as a bombing target.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The equipment was moved to the Soviet Union and was put into service there as the Moscow–Kashira HVDC system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The Moscow–Kashira system and the 1954 connection by Uno Lamm's group at ASEA between the mainland of Sweden and the island of Gotland marked the beginning of the modern era of HVDC transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Mercury arc valves were common in systems designed up to 1972, the last mercury arc HVDC system (the Nelson River Bipole 1 system in Manitoba, Canada) having been put into service in stages between 1972 and 1977.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since then, all mercury arc systems have been either shut down or converted to use solid-state devices.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The last HVDC system to use mercury arc valves was the Inter-Island HVDC link between the North and South Islands of New Zealand, which used them on one of its two poles.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The mercury arc valves were decommissioned on 1 August 2012, ahead of the commissioning of replacement thyristor converters.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The development of thyristor valves for HVDC began in the late 1960s.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The first complete HVDC scheme based on thyristor was the Eel River scheme in Canada, which was built by General Electric and went into service in 1972.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since 1977, new HVDC systems have used solid-state devices, in most cases thyristors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Like mercury arc valves, thyristors require connection to an external AC circuit in HVDC applications to turn them on and off.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC using thyristors is also known as *line-commutated converter* (LCC) HVDC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] On March 15, 1979, a 1920 MW thyristor based direct current connection between Cabora Bassa and Johannesburg (1,410 km; 880 mi) was energized.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The conversion equipment was built in 1974 by Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AG (AEG), and Brown, Boveri & Cie (BBC) and Siemens were partners in the project.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Service interruptions of several years were a result of a civil war in Mozambique.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The transmission voltage of ±533 kV was the highest in the world at the time.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Line-commutated converters have some limitations in their use for HVDC systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This results from requiring a period of *reverse* voltage to affect the turn off.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An attempt to address these limitations is the capacitor-commutated converter (CCC).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The CCC has series capacitors inserted into the AC line connections.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] CCC has remained only a niche application because of the advent of voltage-source converters (VSCs) which more directly address turn-off issues.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Widely used in motor drives since the 1980s, voltage-source converters (VSCs) started to appear in HVDC in 1997 with the experimental Hellsjön–Grängesberg project in Sweden.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] By the end of 2011, this technology had captured a significant proportion of the HVDC market.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The development of higher rated insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs), gate turn-off thyristors (GTOs), and integrated gate-commutated thyristors (IGCTs), has made HVDC systems more economical and reliable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This is because modern IGBTs incorporate a short-circuit failure mode, wherein should an IGBT fail, it is mechanically shorted.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Therefore, modern VSC HVDC converter stations are designed with sufficient redundancy to guarantee operation over their entire service lives.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] They have extended the use of HVDC down to blocks as small as a few tens of megawatts and overhead lines as short as a few dozen kilometers.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] There are several different variants of VSC technology: most installations built until 2012 use pulse-width modulation in a circuit that is effectively an ultra-high-voltage motor drive.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] More recent installations, including HVDC PLUS and HVDC MaxSine, are based on variants of a converter called a *modular multilevel converter* (MMC).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Multilevel converters have the advantage that they allow harmonic filtering equipment to be reduced or eliminated altogether.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] By way of comparison, AC harmonic filters of typical line-commutated converter stations cover nearly half of the converter station area.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With time, voltage-source converter systems will probably replace all installed simple thyristor-based systems, including the highest DC power transmission applications.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A long-distance, point-to-point HVDC transmission scheme generally has lower overall investment cost and lower losses than an equivalent AC transmission scheme.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Although HVDC conversion equipment at the terminal stations is costly, the total DC transmission-line costs over long distances are lower than for an AC line of the same distance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC requires less conductor per unit distance than an AC line, as there is no need to support three phases and there is no skin effect.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] AC systems use a higher peak voltage for the same power, increasing insulator costs.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Depending on voltage level and construction details, HVDC transmission losses are quoted at 3.5% per 1,000 km (620 mi), about 50% less than AC (6.7%) lines at the same voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This is because direct current transfers only active power and thus causes lower losses than alternating current, which transfers both active and reactive power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In other words, transmitting electric AC power over long distances inevitably results in a phase shift between voltage and current.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Because of this phase shift the effective Power = Current × Voltage, where × designates a vector product, decreases.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since DC power has no phase, the phase shift cannot occur in the DC case.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In addition HVDC is particularly useful for submarine cables.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With submarine AC cables, induction and capacitance with the surrounding sea water causes larger than normal losses, which HVDC lacks, and so HVDC submarine cables can be much longer.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC transmission may also be selected for other technical benefits.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC can transfer power between separate AC networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC power flow between separate AC systems can be automatically controlled to support either network during transient conditions, but without the risk that a major power-system collapse in one network will lead to a collapse in the second.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The controllability feature is also useful where control of energy trading is needed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Long undersea or underground high-voltage cables have a high electrical capacitance compared with overhead transmission lines since the live conductors within the cable are surrounded by a relatively thin layer of insulation (the dielectric), and a metal sheath.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The geometry is that of a long coaxial capacitor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The total capacitance increases with the length of the cable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This capacitance is in a parallel circuit with the load.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Where alternating current is used for cable transmission, additional current must flow in the cable to charge this cable capacitance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Another way to look at this is to realize, that such capacitance causes a phase shift between voltage and current, and thus decrease of the transmitted power, which is a vector product of voltage and current.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Additional energy losses also occur as a result of dielectric losses in the cable insulation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For a sufficiently long AC cable, the entire current-carrying ability of the conductor would be needed to supply the charging current alone.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This cable capacitance issue limits the length and power-carrying ability of AC power cables.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] However, if direct current is used, the cable capacitance is charged only when the cable is first energized or if the voltage level changes; there is no additional current required.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] DC powered cables are limited only by their temperature rise and Ohm's law.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Although some leakage current flows *through* the dielectric insulator, this effect is also present in AC systems and is small compared to the cable's rated current.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The capacitive effect of long underground or undersea cables in AC transmission applications also applies to AC overhead lines, although to a much lesser extent.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Nevertheless, for a long AC overhead transmission line, the current flowing just to charge the line capacitance can be significant, and this reduces the capability of the line to carry useful current to the load at the remote end.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Another factor that reduces the useful current-carrying ability of AC lines is the skin effect, which causes a nonuniform distribution of current over the cross-sectional area of the conductor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Transmission line conductors operating with direct current suffer from neither constraint.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Therefore, for the same conductor losses (or heating effect), a given conductor can carry more power to the load when operating with HVDC than AC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The power delivered in an AC system is defined by the root mean square (RMS) of an AC voltage, but RMS is only about 71% of the peak voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Because HVDC allows power transmission between unsynchronized AC distribution systems, it can help increase system stability, by preventing cascading failures from propagating from one part of a wider power transmission grid to another.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Changes in load that would cause portions of an AC network to become unsynchronized and to separate, would not similarly affect a DC link, and the power flow through the DC link would tend to stabilize the AC network.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The magnitude and direction of power flow through a DC link can be directly controlled and changed as needed to support the AC networks at either end of the DC link.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The disadvantages of HVDC are in conversion, switching, control, availability, and maintenance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC is less reliable and has lower availability than alternating current (AC) systems, mainly due to the extra conversion equipment.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Single-pole systems have availability of about 98.5%, with about a third of the downtime unscheduled due to faults.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Fault-tolerant bipole systems provide high availability for 50% of the link capacity, but availability of the full capacity is about 97% to 98%.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The required converter stations are expensive and have limited overload capacity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] At smaller transmission distances, the losses in the converter stations may be bigger than in an AC transmission line for the same distance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The cost of the converters may not be offset by reductions in line construction cost and power line loss.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Operating an HVDC scheme requires many spare parts to be kept, often exclusively for one system, as HVDC systems are less standardized than AC systems and technology changes more quickly.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In contrast to AC systems, realizing multi-terminal systems is complex (especially with line commutated converters), as is expanding existing schemes to multi-terminal systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Controlling power flow in a multi-terminal DC system requires good communication between all the terminals; power flow must be actively regulated by the converter control system instead of relying on the inherent impedance and phase angle properties of an AC transmission line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Multi-terminal systems are therefore rare.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] As of 2012 only two are in service: the Quebec – New England Transmission between Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond and the Sardinia–mainland Italy link which was modified in 1989 to also provide power to the island of Corsica.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC circuit breakers are difficult to build because of arcing: under AC, the voltage inverts and in doing so crosses zero volts dozens of times a second.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An AC arc will self-extinguish at one of these zero-crossing points because there cannot be an arc where there is no potential difference.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] DC will never cross zero volts and never self-extinguish, so arc distance and duration is far greater with DC than the same voltage AC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This means some mechanism must be included in the circuit breaker to force current to zero and extinguish the arc, otherwise arcing and contact wear would be too great to allow reliable switching.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In November 2012, ABB announced the first ultrafast HVDC circuit breaker.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Mechanical circuit breakers are too slow for use in HVDC grids, although they have been used for years in other applications.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Conversely, semiconductor breakers are fast enough but have a high resistance when conducting, wasting energy and generating heat in normal operation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The ABB breaker combines semiconductor and mechanical breakers to produce a *hybrid breaker* with both a fast break time and a low resistance in normal operation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An April 2010 announcement for a 2,000 MW, 64 km (40 mi) line between Spain and France is estimated at €700 million.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This includes the cost of a tunnel through the Pyrenees.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] At the heart of an HVDC converter station, the equipment that performs the conversion between AC and DC is referred to as the *converter*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Almost all HVDC converters are inherently capable of converting from AC to DC (*rectification*) and from DC to AC (*inversion*), although in many HVDC systems, the system as a whole is optimized for power flow in only one direction.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Irrespective of how the converter itself is designed, the station that is operating (at a given time) with power flow from AC to DC is referred to as the *rectifier* and the station that is operating with power flow from DC to AC is referred to as the *inverter*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Early HVDC systems used electromechanical conversion (the Thury system), but all HVDC systems built since the 1940s have used electronic converters.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Most of the HVDC systems in operation today are based on line-commutated converters (LCCs).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The basic LCC configuration uses a three-phase bridge rectifier known as a *six-pulse bridge*, containing six electronic switches, each connecting one of the three phases to one of the two DC rails.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A complete switching element is usually referred to as a *valve*, irrespective of its construction.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] However, with a phase change only every 60°, considerable harmonic distortion is produced at both the DC and AC terminals when this arrangement is used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An enhancement of this arrangement uses 12 valves in a *twelve-pulse bridge*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The AC is split into two separate three-phase supplies before transformation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] One of the sets of supplies is then configured to have a star (wye) secondary, and the other a delta secondary, establishing a 30° phase difference between the two sets of three phases.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With twelve valves connecting each of the two sets of three phases to the two DC rails, there is a phase change every 30°, and harmonics are considerably reduced.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For this reason, the twelve-pulse system has become standard on most line-commutated converter HVDC systems built since the 1970s.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With line commutated converters, the converter has only one degree of freedom – the *firing angle*, which represents the time delay between the voltage across a valve becoming positive (at which point the valve would start to conduct if it were made from diodes) and the thyristors being turned on.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The DC output voltage of the converter steadily becomes less positive as the firing angle is increased: firing angles of up to 90° correspond to rectification and result in positive DC voltages, while firing angles above 90° correspond to inversion and result in negative DC voltages.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The practical upper limit for the firing angle is about 150–160° because above this, the valve would have insufficient turnoff time.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Early LCC systems used mercury-arc valves, which were rugged but required high maintenance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Because of this, many mercury-arc HVDC systems were built with bypass switchgear across each six-pulse bridge so that the HVDC scheme could be operated in six-pulse mode for short maintenance periods.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The last mercury arc system, at the HVDC Inter-Island link, was decommissioned on 1 August 2012.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The thyristor valve was first used in HVDC systems in 1972.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The thyristor is a solid-state semiconductor device similar to the diode, but with an extra control terminal that is used to switch the device on at a particular instant during the AC cycle.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Because the voltages in HVDC systems, up to 800 kV in some cases, far exceed the breakdown voltages of the thyristors used, HVDC thyristor valves are built using large numbers of thyristors in series.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Additional passive components such as grading capacitors and resistors need to be connected in parallel with each thyristor in order to ensure that the voltage across the valve is evenly shared between the thyristors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The thyristor plus its grading circuits and other auxiliary equipment is known as a *thyristor level*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Each thyristor valve will typically contain tens or hundreds of thyristor levels, each operating at a different (high) potential with respect to earth.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The command information to turn on the thyristors therefore cannot simply be sent using a wire connection – it needs to be isolated.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The isolation method can be magnetic but is usually optical.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Two optical methods are used: indirect and direct optical triggering.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In the indirect optical triggering method, low-voltage control electronics send light pulses along optical fibers to the *high-side* control electronics, which derives its power from the voltage across each thyristor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The alternative direct optical triggering method dispenses with most of the high-side electronics, instead using light pulses from the control electronics to switch light-triggered thyristors (LTTs).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In a line-commutated converter, the DC current (usually) cannot change direction; it flows through a large inductance and can be considered almost constant.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] On the AC side, the converter behaves approximately as a current source, injecting both grid-frequency and harmonic currents into the AC network.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For this reason, a line-commutated converter for HVDC is also considered as a *current-source inverter*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Because thyristors can only be turned on (not off) by control action, the control system has only one degree of freedom – when to turn on the thyristor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This is an important limitation in some circumstances.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With some other types of semiconductor devices such as the insulated-gate bipolar transistor (IGBT), both turn-on and turn-off can be controlled, giving a second degree of freedom.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] As a result, they can be used to make *self-commutated converters*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In such converters, the electric polarity of DC voltage is usually fixed and the DC voltage, being smoothed by a large capacitance, can be considered constant.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For this reason, an HVDC converter using IGBTs is usually referred to as a *voltage-sourced converter*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The additional controllability gives many advantages, notably the ability to switch the IGBTs on and off many times per cycle in order to improve the harmonic performance.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Being self-commutated, the converter no longer relies on synchronous machines in the AC system for its operation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A voltage-sourced converter can therefore feed power to an AC network consisting only of passive loads, something which is impossible with LCC HVDC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] HVDC systems based on voltage-sourced converters normally use the six-pulse connection because the converter produces much less harmonic distortion than a comparable LCC and the twelve-pulse connection is unnecessary.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Most of the VSC HVDC systems built until 2012 were based on the *two-level converter*, which can be thought of as a six-pulse bridge in which the thyristors have been replaced by IGBTs with inverse-parallel diodes and the DC smoothing reactors have been replaced by DC smoothing capacitors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Such converters derive their name from the discrete, two voltage levels at the AC output of each phase that correspond to the electrical potentials of the positive and negative DC terminals.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Pulse-width modulation (PWM) is usually used to improve the harmonic distortion of the converter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The IGBTs in each submodule either bypass the capacitor or connect it into the circuit, allowing the valve to synthesize a stepped voltage with very low levels of harmonic distortion.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] At the AC side of each converter, transformers—often a bank of three single-phase transformers—isolate the station from the AC supply to provide a local earth and to achieve the correct DC voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Converter transformers for LCC HVDC schemes are quite specialized because of the high levels of harmonic currents that flow through them, and because the secondary winding insulation experiences a permanent DC voltage, which affects the design of the insulating structure inside the tank.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In LCC systems, the transformers also need to provide the 30° phase shift required for harmonic cancellation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Converter transformers for VSC HVDC systems are usually simpler and more conventional in design than those for LCC HVDC systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A major drawback of HVDC systems using line-commutated converters is that the converters inherently consume reactive power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The AC current flowing into the converter from the AC system lags behind the AC voltage so that, irrespective of the direction of active power flow, the converter always absorbs reactive power, behaving in the same way as a shunt reactor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The reactive power absorbed is at least 0.5 Mvar/MW under ideal conditions and can be higher than this when the converter is operating at higher than usual firing or extinction angle, or reduced DC voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Although at HVDC converter stations connected directly to power stations some of the reactive power may be provided by the generators themselves, in most cases the reactive power consumed by the converter must be provided by banks of shunt capacitors connected at the AC terminals of the converter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The shunt capacitors are usually connected directly to the grid voltage but in some cases may be connected to a lower voltage via a tertiary winding on the converter transformer.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since the reactive power consumed depends on the active power being transmitted, the shunt capacitors usually need to be subdivided into a number of switchable banks (typically four per converter) in order to prevent a surplus of reactive power being generated at low transmitted power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The shunt capacitors are almost always provided with tuning reactors and, where necessary, damping resistors so that they can perform a dual role as harmonic filters.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] VSCs, on the other hand, can either produce or consume reactive power on demand, with the result that usually no separate shunt capacitors are needed (other than those required purely for filtering).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] All electronic power converters generate some degree of harmonic distortion on the AC and DC systems to which they are connected, and HVDC converters are no exception.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With the recently developed MMCs, levels of harmonic distortion may be practically negligible, but with line-commutated converters and simpler types of VSCs, considerable harmonic distortion may be produced on both the AC and DC sides of the converter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] As a result, harmonic filters are nearly always required at the AC terminals of such converters, and in HVDC transmission schemes using overhead lines, may also be required on the DC side.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The basic building block of a line-commutated HVDC converter is the *six-pulse bridge*.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This arrangement produces very high levels of harmonic distortion.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] It is very costly to provide harmonic filters capable of suppressing such harmonics, so a variant known as the *twelve-pulse bridge*, consisting of two six-pulse bridges in series with a 30° phase shift between them, is nearly always used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The task of suppressing harmonics from this arrangement is still challenging, but manageable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Line-commutated converters for HVDC are usually include combinations of harmonic filters designed to deal with the 11th and 13th harmonics on the AC side, and 12th harmonic on the DC side.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Sometimes, high-pass filters are included to deal with 23rd, 25th, 35th, 37th... on the AC side and 24th, 36th... on the DC side.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Sometimes, the AC filters provide damping at lower-order, *noncharacteristic* harmonics such as 3rd or 5th harmonics.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Detailed knowledge of the *harmonic impedance* of the AC system, at a wide range of frequencies, is needed in order to design the AC filters.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] DC filters are required only for HVDC transmission systems involving overhead lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With the rise in digital mobile telecommunications systems, which are much less susceptible to this type of interference, and fiber optic communication which is immune, DC filters are becoming less important for HVDC systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Some types of voltage-sourced converters may produce such low levels of harmonic distortion that no filters are required.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] However, converter types such as the *two-level* converter, used with pulse-width modulation (PWM), still require some filtering, albeit less than on line-commutated converter systems.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In two-level converters, the harmonic spectrum is shifted to higher frequencies compared to line-commutated converters.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The dominant harmonic frequencies are sidebands of the PWM frequency and multiples thereof.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In HVDC applications, the PWM frequency is typically around 1 to 2 kHz.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The higher frequencies allow the filter equipment to be smaller.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In a monopole configuration, one of the terminals of the rectifier is connected to earth ground using an electrode.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The other terminal, at high voltage relative to ground, is connected to a transmission line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With no metallic return conductor installed, return current flows in the earth (or water) between two stations.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This arrangement is a type of single-wire earth return system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The electrodes are usually located some tens of kilometers from the stations and are connected to the stations via a medium-voltage electrode line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The design of the electrodes themselves depends on whether they are located on land, on the shore or at sea.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For the monopolar configuration with earth return, the earth current flow is unidirectional, which means that the design of one of the electrodes (the cathode) can be relatively simple, although the design of anode electrode is quite complex due to corrosion issues associated with electrochemistry.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] These effects can be eliminated with the installation of a metallic return conductor between the two ends of the monopolar transmission line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since one terminal of the converters is connected to earth, the return conductor need not be insulated for the full transmission voltage, which makes it less costly than the high-voltage conductor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The decision of whether or not to use a metallic return conductor is based upon economic, technical and environmental factors.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Modern monopolar systems for pure overhead lines typically carry 2 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] If underground or underwater cables are used, the typical value is 1 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Most monopolar systems are designed for future bipolar expansion.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Transmission line towers may be designed to carry two conductors, even if only one is used initially for the monopole transmission system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The second conductor is either unused, used as electrode line or connected in parallel with the other (as in case of Baltic Cable).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An alternative is to use two high-voltage conductors, operating at about half of the DC voltage, with only a single converter at each end.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In this arrangement, known as the *symmetrical monopole*, the converters are earthed only via a high impedance and there is no earth current.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The symmetrical monopole arrangement is uncommon with line-commutated converters (the NorNed interconnector being a rare example) but is very common with voltage-sourced converters when cables are used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In bipolar transmission, a pair of conductors is used, each at a high potential with respect to ground, in opposite polarity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Since these conductors must be insulated for the full voltage, the transmission line cost is higher than a monopole with a return conductor.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Bipolar systems may carry as much as 4 GW at voltages of ±660 kV with a single converter per pole, as on the Ningdong–Shandong project in China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With a power rating of 2 GW per twelve-pulse converter, the converters for that project were, as of 2010, the most powerful HVDC converters ever built.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Even higher powers can be achieved by connecting two or more twelve-pulse converters in series in each pole, as is done in the ±800 kV Xiangjiaba–Shanghai project in China, which uses two twelve-pulse converter bridges in each pole, each rated at 400 kV DC and 1.6 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Submarine cable installations initially commissioned as a monopole may be upgraded with additional cables and operated as a bipole.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A bipolar scheme can be implemented so that the polarity of one or both poles can be changed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This allows operation as two parallel monopoles, so if one conductor fails, transmission can still continue at reduced capacity.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Losses may increase if ground electrodes and lines are not designed for the extra current in this mode.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] To reduce losses in this case, intermediate switching stations may be installed, at which line segments can be switched off or parallelized.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This configuration was implemented at Inga–Shaba HVDC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A **back-to-back station** (**B2B**) is a plant in which both converters are in the same area, usually in the same building.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The length of the direct current line is kept as short as possible.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The DC voltage in the intermediate circuit can be selected freely at back-to-back stations because of the short conductor length.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The DC voltage is usually selected to be as low as possible, in order to build a small valve hall and to reduce the number of thyristors connected in series in each valve.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] For this reason, at HVDC back-to-back stations, valves with the highest available current rating (in some cases, up to 4,500 A) are used.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The most common configuration of an HVDC link consists of two converter stations connected by an overhead power line or undersea cable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Multi-terminal HVDC links, connecting more than two points, are rare.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The configuration of multiple terminals can be series, parallel, or hybrid (a mixture of series and parallel).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Parallel configuration tends to be used for large-capacity stations, and series for lower-capacity stations.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] An example is the 2,000 MW Quebec - New England Transmission system opened in 1992.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] When it opened in 1992, it was the largest multi-terminal HVDC system in the world.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Multi-terminal systems are difficult to realize using line-commutated converters because reversals of power are effected by reversing the polarity of DC voltage, which affects all converters connected to the system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With voltage-sourced converters, power reversal is achieved instead by reversing the direction of current, making parallel-connected multi-terminal systems much easier to control.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] While addressing environmental targets, China is expanding its grid to keep up with increased power demand.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] China Southern Power Grid started a three-terminal VSC HVDC pilot project in 2011.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The project has designed ratings of ±160 kV at 200 MW-100 MW-50 MW and will be used to bring wind power generated on Nanao island into the mainland Guangdong power grid through 32 km (20 mi) of combination of HVDC land cables, sea cables and overhead lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This project was put into operation on December 19, 2013.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In India, the multi-terminal North-East Agra project was commissioned in 2015–2016.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] It is rated 6,000 MW, and it transmits power on a ±800 kV bipolar line from two converter stations, at Biswanath Chariali and Alipurduar, in the east to a converter at Agra, a distance of 1,728 km (1,074 mi).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Cross-Skagerrak consisted since 1993 of three poles, from which two were switched in parallel and the third used an opposite polarity with a higher transmission voltage.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This configuration ended in 2014 when poles 1 and 2 again were rebuilt to work in bipole and pole 3 (LCC) works in bipole with a new pole 4 (VSC).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This is the first HVDC transmission where LCC and VSC poles cooperate in a bipole.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This configuration ended in 2012 when the two old converters were replaced with a single, new, thyristor converter.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] A scheme patented in 2004 is intended for conversion of existing AC transmission lines to HVDC.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Two of the three circuit conductors are operated as a bipole.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The third conductor is used as a parallel monopole, equipped with reversing valves (or parallel valves connected in reverse polarity).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This allows heavier currents to be carried by the bipole conductors, and full use of the installed third conductor for energy transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] High currents can be circulated through the line conductors even when load demand is low, for removal of ice.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] As of 2012, no tripole conversions are in operation, although a transmission line in India has been converted to bipole HVDC (HVDC Sileru-Barsoor).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Corona discharge is the creation of ions in a fluid (such as air) by the presence of a strong electric field.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Electrons are torn from neutral air, and either the positive ions or the electrons are attracted to the conductor, while the charged particles drift.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] This effect can cause considerable power loss, create audible and radio-frequency interference, generate toxic compounds such as oxides of nitrogen and ozone, and bring forth arcing.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Both AC and DC transmission lines can generate coronas, in the former case in the form of oscillating particles, in the latter a constant wind.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Due to the space charge formed around the conductors, an HVDC system may have about half the loss per unit length of a high voltage AC system carrying the same amount of power.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] With monopolar transmission the choice of polarity of the energized conductor leads to a degree of control over the corona discharge.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] In particular, the polarity of the ions emitted can be controlled, which may have an environmental impact on ozone creation.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] Negative coronas generate considerably more ozone than positive coronas, and generate it further *downwind* of the power line, creating the potential for health effects.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p01] The use of a *positive* voltage will reduce the ozone impacts of monopole HVDC power lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Offshore windfarms also require undersea cables, and their turbines are unsynchronized.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] In very long-distance connections between two locations, such as power transmission from a large hydroelectric power plant at a remote site to an urban area, HVDC transmission systems may appropriately be used; several schemes of these kind have been built.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] For interconnectors to Siberia, Canada, India, and the Scandinavian North, the decreased line-costs of HVDC also make it applicable, see List of HVDC projects.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Other applications are noted throughout this article.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] AC transmission lines can interconnect only synchronized AC networks with the same frequency with limits on the allowable phase difference between the two ends of the line.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Many areas that wish to share power have unsynchronized networks.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The power grids of the UK, Northern Europe and continental Europe are not united into a single synchronized network.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Continental North America, while operating at 60 Hz throughout, is divided into regions which are unsynchronized: East, West, Texas, Quebec, and Alaska.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Brazil and Paraguay, which share the enormous Itaipu Dam hydroelectric plant, operate on 60 Hz and 50 Hz respectively.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] However, HVDC systems make it possible to interconnect unsynchronized AC networks, and also add the possibility of controlling AC voltage and reactive power flow.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] A generator connected to a long AC transmission line may become unstable and fall out of synchronization with a distant AC power system.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] An HVDC transmission link may make it economically feasible to use remote generation sites.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Wind farms located off-shore may use HVDC systems to collect power from multiple unsynchronized generators for transmission to the shore by an underwater cable.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] In general, however, an HVDC power line will interconnect two AC regions of the power-distribution grid.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Machinery to convert between AC and DC power adds a considerable cost in power transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The conversion from AC to DC is known as rectification, and from DC to AC as inversion.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Above a certain break-even distance (about 50 km; 31 mi for submarine cables, and perhaps 600–800 km; 370–500 mi for overhead cables), the lower cost of the HVDC electrical conductors outweighs the cost of the electronics.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The conversion electronics also present an opportunity to effectively manage the power grid by means of controlling the magnitude and direction of power flow.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] An additional advantage of the existence of HVDC links, therefore, is potential increased stability in the transmission grid.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] A number of studies have highlighted the potential benefits of very wide area super grids based on HVDC since they can mitigate the effects of intermittency by averaging and smoothing the outputs of large numbers of geographically dispersed wind farms or solar farms.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Czisch's study concludes that a grid covering the fringes of Europe could bring 100% renewable power (70% wind, 30% biomass) at close to today's prices.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] There has been debate over the technical feasibility of this proposal and the political risks involved in energy transmission across a large number of international borders.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The construction of such green power superhighways is advocated in a white paper that was released by the American Wind Energy Association and the Solar Energy Industries Association in 2009.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Clean Line Energy Partners is developing four HVDC lines in the US for long-distance electric power transmission.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Meanwhile, the recently founded Union of the Mediterranean has embraced a Mediterranean Solar Plan to import large amounts of concentrated solar power into Europe from North Africa and the Middle East.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Japan-Taiwan-Philippines HVDC interconnector was proposed in 2020.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The purpose of this interconnector is to facilitate cross-border renewable power trading with Indonesia and Australia, in preparation for the future Asian Pacific Super Grid.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] UHVDC (ultrahigh-voltage direct-current) is shaping up to be the latest technological front in high voltage DC transmission technology.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] UHVDC is defined as DC voltage transmission of above 800 kV (HVDC is generally just 100 to 800 kV).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] One of the problems with current UHVDC supergrids is that – although less than AC transmission or DC transmission at lower voltages – they still suffer from power loss as the length is extended.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] A typical loss for 800 kV lines is 2.6% over 800 km (500 mi).
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] Increasing the transmission voltage on such lines reduces the power loss, but until recently, the interconnectors required to bridge the segments were prohibitively expensive.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] However, with advances in manufacturing, it is becoming more and more feasible to build UHVDC lines.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] In 2010, ABB built the world's first 800 kV UHVDC in China.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] The Zhundong–Wannan UHVDC line with 1100 kV, 3,400 km (2,100 mi) length and 12 GW capacity was completed in 2018.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] As of 2020, at least thirteen UHVDC transmission lines in China have been completed.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] While the majority of recent UHVDC technology deployment is in China, it has also been deployed in South America as well as other parts of Asia.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] In India, a 1,830 km (1,140 mi), 800 kV, 6 GW line between Raigarh and Pugalur was expected to be completed in 2019.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] In Brazil, the Xingu-Estreito line over 2,076 km (1,290 mi) with 800 kV and 4 GW was completed in 2017, and the Xingu-Rio line over 2,543 km (1,580 mi) with 800 kV and 4 GW was completed in 2019, both to transmit the energy from Belo Monte Dam.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] As of 2020, no UHVDC line (≥ 800 kV) exists in Europe or North America.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] A 1,100 kV link in China was completed in 2019 over a distance of 3,300 km (2,100 mi) with a power capacity of 12 GW.
[src:higashi-shimizu-frequency-converter/hvdc-p02] With this dimension, intercontinental connections become possible which could help to deal with the fluctuations of wind power and photovoltaics.
